# Git identity for this repo

Every commit made in this project (including from the agent via terminal) must show **Umang** as author and committer, not “Cursor Agent”, “cursoragent”, or other tool defaults.

**Canonical identity**

- Name: `Umang`
- Email: `leoumang007@gmail.com`

**How to commit (preferred)**

Do **not** change the user’s global or system git config unless they explicitly ask. For each commit, set author and committer in the environment:

```bash
GIT_AUTHOR_NAME="Umang" GIT_AUTHOR_EMAIL="leoumang007@gmail.com" \
GIT_COMMITTER_NAME="Umang" GIT_COMMITTER_EMAIL="leoumang007@gmail.com" \
git commit -m "Your message"
```

On PowerShell:

```powershell
$env:GIT_AUTHOR_NAME="Umang"; $env:GIT_AUTHOR_EMAIL="leoumang007@gmail.com"; $env:GIT_COMMITTER_NAME="Umang"; $env:GIT_COMMITTER_EMAIL="leoumang007@gmail.com"; git commit -m "Your message"
```

`git commit --author="Umang <leoumang007@gmail.com>"` sets **author** only; **committer** can still come from local config—use the env vars above when both must be Umang.

If the user asks to rewrite existing commits that used the wrong identity, use history rewrite (e.g. `git filter-repo` / `git filter-branch`) and remind them that a force-push may be required.
